<span id="v.iii.xxix-p1"></span> <span class="c12"><span
id="v.iii.xxix-p1.1"></span>Chapter XXVII.</span>

<span id="v.iii.xxix-p2"></span><span class="c12"><span
id="v.iii.xxix-p2.1"></span>Dionysius</span>, <span
id="fr_2426"></span>[2427](#fn_2426.md) bishop of the church of Corinth,
was of so great eloquence and industry that he taught not only the
people of his own city and province but also those of other provinces
and cities by his letters. Of these one is *To the Lacedæmonians,*
another *To the Athenians,* a third *To the Nicomedians,* a fourth *To
the Cretans,* a fifth *To the church at Amastrina and to the other
churches of Pontus,* a sixth *To the Gnosians and to Pinytus bishop of
the same city,* a seventh *To the Romans,* addressed to Soter their
bishop, an eighth *To Chrysophora* a holy woman. He flourished in the
reign of Marcus Antoninus Verus and Lucius Aurelius Commodus.

